A '''citizen legislature''' is a [[Legislature|legislative chamber]] made up primarily of citizens who have a full-time occupation besides being a legislator. Such citizen legislatures can be found on the state level, as in some [[U.S.]] states, or on the national level as in [[Switzerland]].<ref name="urlMiliz-Parlamentswissinfo.ch">{{cite web |url=http://www.swissinfo.ch/ger/die-legislative-ist-ein-miliz-parlament/162442 |title=Die Legislative ist ein Miliz-Parlament - SWI swissinfo.ch |format= |work= |accessdate=2016-12-13}}</ref>
Legislatures in the U.S. considered to be citizen legislatures include [[Idaho]],<ref>[http://www.legislature.idaho.gov/about/citizenlegislature.htm Idaho State Legislature - Idaho's Citizen Legislature<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[New Mexico]], [[North Carolina]], [[Oregon]],<ref>[http://www.leg.state.or.us/ Oregon State Legislature<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110110195651/http://www.leg.state.or.us/ |date=January 10, 2011 }}</ref> [[Utah]],<ref>[http://le.utah.gov/code/CONST/htm/00I06_001600.htm Utah Constitution - Article VI, Section 16 - Duration of sessions.]</ref> and [[Wyoming]].<ref>[http://legisweb.state.wy.us/leginfo/guide98.htm Citizen's Guide to the Legislature<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Many other states in the US, by contrast, have a [[professional legislature]]. [[James Madison]] wrote in Federalist No. 62 that "It is not possible that an assembly of men called for the most part from pursuits of a private nature, continued in appointment for a short time, and led by no permanent motive to devote intervals of public occupation to a study of the laws, the affairs, and the comprehensive interests of their country, should, if left wholly to themselves, escape a variety of important errors in the exercise of their legislative trust."<ref>[http://www.constitution.org/fed/federa62.htm]</ref>
