For electoral purposes, the whole of Cyprus is considered to be a Commonwealth country; hence, anyone who holds a [[Cypriot passport]] or a [[Northern Cypriot passport]] is considered to be a Commonwealth citizen (but not a person who is solely a Turkish citizen without any form of Cypriot nationality).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/43954/Part-B-Entitlement-to-register-March-2010.pdf |title=Part B – Entitlement to register (Section 6.28)|format=PDF |date=March 2010 |accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref>

[[The Gambia]] left the Commonwealth on 3 October 2013 and was removed from the schedule on 12 November 2015 by virtue of The British Nationality (The Gambia) Order 2015.  The new Gambian government elected in 2017 has stated that it will apply to re-join. The Gambia rejoined the Commonwealth on 8 February 2018, after the Commonwealth Secretariat confirmed their application had been approved unanimously by Commonwealth Member States.<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/news/the-gambia-rejoins-the-commonwealth</ref> It was then added back to the schedule on 22 June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=The British Nationality (The Gambia) Order 2018 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2018/620/pdfs/uksi_20180620_en.pdf |website=legislation.gov.uk |accessdate=29 June 2018 |date=23 May 2018}}</ref>

[[Maldives]] left the Commonwealth on 13 October 2016 and was removed from the schedule on 12 May 2017 by virtue of The British Nationality (Maldives) Order 2017.

==Privileges of Commonwealth citizens in other countries==
Although the rights and privileges (if any) for non-national Commonwealth citizens differ from country to country, a number of Commonwealth countries grant them more privileges than 'aliens' (i.e. non-Commonwealth foreign nationals), but not the full privileges enjoyed by the country's own nationals.

===Right to vote===
{{See also|Right of foreigners to vote}}
The following Commonwealth countries allow citizens from other Commonwealth countries to vote:
* {{flagcountry|Antigua and Barbuda}}. The Representation of the People (Amendment) Act (2002) permits Commonwealth citizens who have lived in Antigua and Barbuda for at least 3 years to register to vote in the constituency where they have resided for at least 1 month.
* {{flagcountry|Australia}}. Australia has abolished the status of [[British subject]] with effect from 26 January 1984. However, British subjects and Commonwealth citizens (excluding South African citizens) and Irish citizens who were on the federal electoral roll on 25 January 1984 can vote. If they leave Australia and their enrolment has lapsed, they are still eligible to re-enrol upon their return to Australia.<ref>{{cite web|author=&nbsp;Change name |url=http://www.aec.gov.au/Enrolling_to_vote/British_subjects.htm |title=Australian Electoral Commission: British Subjects Eligibility |publisher=Aec.gov.au |date=}}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Barbados}}. By virtue of the [[Constitution of Barbados]] under Sec. 41A. of CAP. 5, and the ''Representation of the People's Act'', CAP. 12, Section 7; Commonwealth citizens are given the right to vote and stand for [[Elections in Barbados|election]] to the [[Parliament of Barbados]] under proscribed stipulations.<ref>{{cite news |title='Only citizens should vote' |first=Geralyn |last=Edward |url=http://www.nationnews.com/articles/view/only-citizens-should-vote/ |agency= |newspaper=[[The Daily Nation (Barbados)|Nation Newspaper]] |publisher= |location= |date=1 April 2012 |page= |pages= |at= |accessdate=3 November 2012 |trans-title=|quote=Philip 'Jimmy' Serrao, who was EBC chairman for 15 years, said the provision in Barbados' laws that allowed Commonwealth citizens to vote in general elections after residing here for three years ought to be changed. What's more, Serrao was firm in his belief that only Barbadian citizens should have the right to elect representatives to govern this country. Serrao, a Queen's Counsel, who chaired the EBC from 1995 to 2010, told the SUNDAY SUN that citizens of Barbados of the Commonwealth who have resided in Barbados for at least three years, were over the age of 18 and resided in the constituency for three months, could influence who made it into the House of Assembly. |ref=}}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Belize}}. Non-Belizean Commonwealth citizens who are either domiciled or who have lived for the past 12 months in Belize are eligible to register to vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.gov.bz/modules/smartfaq/faq.php?faqid=11|title=Elections FAQs - Facts About Voter Registration - Who is eligible to Register to Vote? : Elections and Boundaries Department - Belize|first=Belize Elections & Boundaries|last=Department|publisher=}}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Dominica}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electoraloffice.gov.dm/?p=115 |title=Government of the Commonwealth of Dominica Electoral Office: Who Can Register to Vote? |publisher=Electoraloffice.gov.dm |date=}}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Grenada}}. Commonwealth citizens who have lived in Grenada for 12 consecutive months are eligible to vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://antiguaobserver.com/new-regulations-governing-citizenship-for-grenada/|title=New Regulations Governing Citizenship for Grenada |publisher=Antiguaobserver.com |date=}}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Guyana}}. By virtue of Article 159 of the Constitution, Commonwealth citizens aged 18 or over who are "domiciled and resident" in Guyana are eligible to vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gecom.org.gy/elections_in_guyana.html |title=Guyana Elections Commission: Elections in Guyana |publisher=Gecom.org.gy |date=13 February 2001}}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Jamaica}}. Non-Jamaican Commonwealth citizens can register to vote in all elections as long as they are ordinarily resident in Jamaica.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pdba.georgetown.edu/Electoral/Jamaica/jamrep.html |title=Representation of the People Act 1944, Sections 5(2)(a) and 111(3)(b) |publisher=Pdba.georgetown.edu |date=}}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Malawi}}. By virtue of Section 77(2)(a) of the Constitution, all foreign nationals – including Commonwealth citizens – who have lived in Malawi for 7 years can register to vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdnp.org.mw/constitut/chapter7.html |title=Malawi Constitution Section 77 |publisher=Sdnp.org.mw |date=}}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Mauritius}}. By virtue of Section 42(1) of the Constitution, a Commonwealth citizen aged 18 or over on 15 August in the year of registration, and who has either lived in Mauritius for at least two years prior to 1 January in the year of registration or who is domiciled in Mauritius on 1 January in the year of registration may vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.mu/portal/site/eco/menuitem.61d257cad79ffcba9459d9a365d521ca/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616061744/http://www.gov.mu/portal/site/eco/menuitem.61d257cad79ffcba9459d9a365d521ca/ |archivedate=16 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|New Zealand}}. All foreign nationals – including Commonwealth citizens – who are permanent residents (i.e. in possession of an indefinite visa) are obliged to register to vote at the address where they have lived for at least one month, and can continue to vote in New Zealand elections if abroad as long as they have been to New Zealand in the past year.<ref>[http://www.elections.org.nz/enrolment/how-to-enrol/who-can-enrol.html Elections New Zealand: Who can enrol?] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208040544/http://www.elections.org.nz/enrolment/how-to-enrol/who-can-enrol.html |date=8 February 2013 }}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}.
* {{flagcountry|Saint Lucia}}. Commonwealth citizens aged 18 or over who have lived in Saint Lucia for 7 years and have lived in their constituency for at least 2 months is eligible to register to vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electoral.gov.lc/ |title=Saint Lucia Electoral Department: Frequently Asked Questions |publisher=Electoral.gov.lc |date=}}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}. Commonwealth citizens aged 18 or over who have lived in St Vincent and the Grenadines for at least 12 months and in their constituency for at least 6 months are eligible to vote in that constituency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pdba.georgetown.edu/Electoral/StVincent/StV&Gr.html |title=St Vincent and the Grenadines Representation of the People Act (1982) |date=28 December 1982}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caribbeanelections.com/elections/vc_elections.asp |title=St Vincent and the Grenadines Elections |publisher=CaribbeanElections |date=28 December 1982 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704195353/http://www.caribbeanelections.com/elections/vc_elections.asp |archivedate=4 July 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Trinidad and Tobago}}. Commonwealth citizens aged 18 or over who have lived for at least one year in Trinidad and Tobago are eligible to vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ebctt.com/ourServices.php |title=Trinidad and Tobago Elections and Boundaries Commission: Services provided |publisher=Ebctt.com |date= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620133109/http://www.ebctt.com/ourServices.php |archivedate=20 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

====British Crown Dependencies====
All British [[Crown Dependencies]] allow citizens from Commonwealth countries to vote:
* {{flagcountry|Guernsey}}. All those – including Commonwealth citizens – who are aged 16 or above and have been ordinarily resident in Guernsey for the past 2 years consecutively (or a total of 5 years at any time) are entitled to register to vote.<ref>[https://www.gov.gg/elections States of Guernsey: Elections and voting]</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Isle of Man}}. All those – including Commonwealth citizens – who are aged 16 or above and have been ordinarily resident in the Isle of Man for the past 12 months are entitled to register to vote.<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.im/cms/images/LEGISLATION/PRINCIPAL/2006/2006-0012/RegistrationofElectorsAct2006_1.pdf Registration of Electors Act 2006, Section 3]</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Jersey}}. All those – including Commonwealth citizens – who are aged 16 or above and have been ordinarily resident in Jersey for the past 2 years consecutively (or for the past 6 months, as well as a total of 5 years at any time) are entitled to register to vote.<ref>[https://www.jerseylaw.je/laws/revised/Pages/16.600.aspx#_Toc472503641 Public Elections (Jersey) Law 2002, Article 5]</ref>

====British Overseas Territories====
The following Overseas Territories of the United Kingdom allow citizens from Commonwealth countries to vote:
* {{flagcountry|Bermuda}}. Non-Bermudian Commonwealth citizens who were registered to vote on 1 May 1976 are eligible to vote.<ref>[http://www.elections.gov.bm/voting-faq.html Bermuda Parliamentary Registry: Voter Eligibility] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310104243/http://www.elections.gov.bm/voting-faq.html |date=10 March 2009 }}</ref>
* {{flagcountry|Gibraltar}}. Commonwealth citizens are eligible to vote in [[elections to the European Parliament]].<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2003/7/section/16 European Parliament (Representation) Act 2003, Section 16]</ref><ref>[http://www.gibraltarlaws.gov.gi/articles/2004-05o.pdf European Parliamentary Elections Act 2004]</ref> In addition, Commonwealth citizens who used to live in Gibraltar but have moved elsewhere can register as an 'overseas elector' and vote in [[elections to the European Parliament]] provided that they were on the Register of Electors in Gibraltar within the past 15 years (the 15 years period begins when they no longer appeared in the Register of Electors, not the date they moved abroad). If they moved abroad before the age of 18, they can still qualify for registration as an 'overseas elector' in [[elections to the European Parliament]], with the 15 years period calculated from the date their parent(s)/guardian ceased to appear in the Register of Electors in Gibraltar.<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2004/293/schedule/4/made The European Parliamentary Elections Regulations 2004, Schedule 4, Paragraph 14]</ref>

* {{flagcountry|Cayman Islands}}. The Cayman Islands is not a member of the Commonwealth as it is a British Overseas Territory and not a sovereign state. Commonwealth citizens who are not [[British Overseas Territories Citizen]]s by virtue of their connection to the Cayman Islands can still vote if on 31 January 1988 they were resident and on the electoral roll in the Islands, and either had a parent born in the Cayman Islands or was ordinarily resident in the Cayman Islands for 7 out of the 9 years preceding registration.<ref>[http://www.electionsoffice.ky/cms/registration-process/45-qualifications-disqualifications-of-an-elector Cayman Islands Elections Office: Qualifications and Disqualifications of an Elector] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719023437/http://www.electionsoffice.ky/cms/registration-process/45-qualifications-disqualifications-of-an-elector |date=19 July 2011 }}</ref>

===Immigration benefits===

Some Commonwealth countries offer visa-free entry for short visits made by Commonwealth citizens. Some Commonwealth countries continue to allow Commonwealth citizens from other countries to become nationals/local citizens by ''registration'' rather than ''naturalisation'', upon preferential terms, e.g. with a shorter required period of residency, although this practice has been discontinued in some countries such as [[New Zealand nationality law#Historical provisions - 1949 to 1977|New Zealand]] and [[Maltese nationality law#Naturalisation as a Maltese citizen|Malta]].

In March 2013, it was announced by Nigeria's Foreign Affairs Minister, Ambassador Olugbenga Ashiru, that a visa free regime is being contemplated by Commonwealth countries for its members to strengthen trade and investment among member nations. As a prelude to accomplishing this, the council of ministers is to present a proposal for the exemption of holders of official and diplomatic passports from visa requirements at the next Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting, CHOGOM, scheduled to hold in Colombo, Sri Lanka.<ref name = "Commonwealth Plans Visa Free Regime">{{cite web|url=http://www.informationng.com/2013/03/commonwealth-plans-visa-free-regime-for-member-states.html |title=Commonwealth Plans Visa Free Regime For Member States |publisher=Informationng.com |date=5 March 2013}}</ref><ref name="Commonwealth plans Visa-Free Policy">{{cite web |url=http://www.businessdayonline.com/NG/index.php/news/284-breaking-news/52582-commonwealth-plans-visa-free-policy-to-boost-trade-investment-among-member-states |title=Commonwealth plans visa-free policy to boost trade, investment among member states |publisher=Businessdayonline.com |date=5 March 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308054219/http://www.businessdayonline.com/NG/index.php/news/284-breaking-news/52582-commonwealth-plans-visa-free-policy-to-boost-trade-investment-among-member-states |archivedate=8 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

The announcement came in the wake of a meeting between Ashiru and the Secretary General of the Commonwealth, Kamalesh Sharma, in Abuja. At the meeting Ashiru and Sharma discussed proposals to make the Commonwealth more relevant to its citizens across the globe including ways the Commonwealth could ease free movement across member countries, strengthen institutions, enhance education, create job opportunities, facilitate development and enhance the living standard of the citizens across the countries of the Commonwealth.<ref name = "Commonwealth Plans Visa Free Regime" /><ref name = "Commonwealth plans Visa-Free Policy" />

Ashiru said, "We also discussed the issue of free movement to promote people to people contact within the Commonwealth. In the past, it used to be that holders of Commonwealth passports could travel within the Commonwealth countries easily without having to go and queue for visas. We are now thinking for ways to ensure that we bring back this old tradition of the Commonwealth. Already, the council of ministers have recommended for approval at the next CHOGOM meeting in Colombo the exemption of holders of official and diplomatic passports within the Commonwealth from the requirement of a visa if they are travelling within the Commonwealth."<ref name = "Commonwealth Plans Visa Free Regime" /><ref name = "Commonwealth plans Visa-Free Policy" />

When approved, he said, other categories of professionals and businessmen would be recommended for similar privileges.<ref name = "Commonwealth Plans Visa Free Regime" /><ref name = "Commonwealth plans Visa-Free Policy" />

===Other rights===
* The right to work in any position (including the civil service) in some instances, except for certain specific positions (e.g. defence, [[Governor-General]] or President, Prime Minister).
* Eligibility to serve in the armed forces of certain countries.
* Eligibility for the [[Commonwealth Scholarship]].

==Consular assistance==
{{See also|Consular assistance}}
In foreign (i.e. non-Commonwealth) countries, the British embassy or consulate is traditionally responsible for Commonwealth citizens whose governments are not represented in the country concerned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/224126/FCOBritsAbroadA4_0713xx.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019062503/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/224126/FCOBritsAbroadA4_0713xx.pdf |archivedate=19 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> A few Commonwealth governments have made alternative arrangements to share the burden, such as the [[Canada-Australia Consular Services Sharing Agreement]],<ref>{{Citation
|url=http://www.voyage.gc.ca/laws_lois/australia-canada-australie-eng.asp
|title=Canada-Australia Consular Services Sharing Agreement
|publisher=Government of Canada
|accessdate=14 December 2007
}}</ref> hence for Canadian and Australian citizens, the British embassy or consulate only provides assistance if neither country is represented. In return, there are a few Australian consulates that are responsible for British nationals because there is no British consulate there. Some Commonwealth governments, such as Singapore and [[Tanzania]], have opted not to receive consular assistance from the United Kingdom.

In other Commonwealth countries, British [[High Commission]]s accept no responsibility for unrepresented Commonwealth citizens, who should look to the host Commonwealth government for quasi-consular assistance. Canadian and Australian citizens are still able to seek consular assistance from each other's high commissions. Additionally, Canadian citizens can seek consular assistance at any British embassy or high commission where Canada is not represented.

===Commonwealth citizen travel documents===

Commonwealth citizens outside the UK are eligible to apply for a [[British emergency passport|British emergency travel document]] if they need to travel urgently and their passport has been lost/stolen/expired (as long as the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|FCO]] has cleared this with the government of the Commonwealth citizen's home country).<ref>[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121212135632/http://centralcontent.fco.gov.uk/resources/en/pdf/central-content-pdfs/5619320/etd-leaflet.pdf Foreign & Commonwealth Office: The new UK Emergency Passport]</ref>

When a British embassy or consulate in a foreign country is required to provide a replacement passport to a Commonwealth citizen whose government is unrepresented in that country, it will issue a British passport with the nationality of the holder marked as "Commonwealth citizen".<ref>
{{Citation
